WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.800
So I'm here to talk about model migration from Excel to R, but I'd like to actually

00:00:11.800 --> 00:00:16.840
begin this presentation with a story.

00:00:16.840 --> 00:00:23.000
So this is a story about a model migration exercise that I did about five or six years

00:00:23.000 --> 00:00:29.799
ago, and it was from Excel to R, subject of this talk, and the ultimate outcome of this

00:00:29.799 --> 00:00:36.200
story was that I really improved my programming skills in the language R. So, you know, this

00:00:36.200 --> 00:00:39.080
is a positive story, right?

00:00:39.080 --> 00:00:43.799
But I don't think it would be interesting to tell a story about just good things happening

00:00:43.799 --> 00:00:44.799
to me.

00:00:44.799 --> 00:00:51.119
I think the best stories have conflict, and in the best stories, things go wrong.

00:00:51.119 --> 00:00:55.160
And this is a story, I'm pleased to say, where the price of my success is that I ended

00:00:55.160 --> 00:00:58.080
up crashing the server.

00:00:58.080 --> 00:01:04.239
And it's doubly tragic, because not only did this happen to me, I was also having to use

00:01:04.239 --> 00:01:07.839
Excel day in, day out, and I know people in the audience, if you've had that experience

00:01:07.839 --> 00:01:10.720
before, that can be a bit of a struggle.

00:01:10.720 --> 00:01:14.919
So let me take you back five or six years ago.

00:01:14.919 --> 00:01:16.160
Where did this all start?

00:01:16.160 --> 00:01:19.879
So this started with my boss at the time.

00:01:19.879 --> 00:01:23.120
This is my boss.

00:01:23.120 --> 00:01:30.080
And my boss comes over to me, and he says, Johnny, I've got a job for you.

00:01:30.080 --> 00:01:31.919
And the job is this.

00:01:31.919 --> 00:01:37.440
So we have a model that we've configured in Microsoft Excel.

00:01:37.440 --> 00:01:39.739
It's slightly complicated.

00:01:39.739 --> 00:01:45.320
It takes multiple people multiple days to actually execute the model.

00:01:45.320 --> 00:01:48.339
And it's highly error-prone process.

00:01:48.339 --> 00:01:52.180
So at the end of it, we often have to check if things have gone wrong.

00:01:52.180 --> 00:01:55.620
There's a lot of validation involved in this process.

00:01:55.620 --> 00:02:00.339
And personally, I think it would be better suited to a programming language like R. So

00:02:00.339 --> 00:02:01.860
would you be interested in doing this?

00:02:01.860 --> 00:02:05.139
So my instinctive reaction is, yeah, that sounds great.

00:02:05.139 --> 00:02:06.480
What's the model?

00:02:06.480 --> 00:02:11.820
So my boss goes on to explain, it's a statistical model, okay?

00:02:11.820 --> 00:02:14.460
And it's also a simulation model.

00:02:14.460 --> 00:02:18.940
So at the time, I was working in financial services.

00:02:18.940 --> 00:02:20.979
And this was for a banking client.

00:02:20.979 --> 00:02:28.380
And what they were interested in was multiple simulations of yearly loss scenarios.

00:02:28.380 --> 00:02:33.100
And after those simulations had been executed, what they wanted to see was, well, if you

00:02:33.100 --> 00:02:39.339
plotted them on a distribution, what would the 99.9th percentile look like?

00:02:39.339 --> 00:02:43.740
And if you think about that, for a yearly loss distribution, that's an event that would

00:02:43.740 --> 00:02:45.779
only happen once in 1,000 years.

00:02:45.779 --> 00:02:47.779
So it's pretty rare.

00:02:47.779 --> 00:02:52.500
And the point about this is, this was not only a complicated model, it was something

00:02:52.500 --> 00:02:54.020
that was quite intensive.

00:02:54.020 --> 00:02:56.179
It needed to be run multiple times.

00:02:56.179 --> 00:02:58.940
And I'm talking 10 to 15 million iterations.

00:02:58.940 --> 00:03:03.619
So I was aware of the challenge that lay before me.

00:03:03.619 --> 00:03:06.660
And so I dived into the Excel model.

00:03:06.660 --> 00:03:11.460
And it's kind of hard to explain to people who haven't worked in financial service or

00:03:11.460 --> 00:03:17.179
industries like this before, where you come across these Excel models, and they're monolithic.

00:03:17.179 --> 00:03:19.259
They're trying to do everything.

00:03:19.259 --> 00:03:26.699
And I think this picture kind of sums up the feeling of walking into one of these things.

00:03:26.699 --> 00:03:30.979
It's a bit like booking an Airbnb, and you turn up in a demolition house.

00:03:30.979 --> 00:03:33.220
But I was resilient.

00:03:33.220 --> 00:03:34.619
I was a resilient individual.

00:03:34.619 --> 00:03:35.979
And I understood the task before me.

00:03:35.979 --> 00:03:39.020
And I wanted to carry this out and prove that I could do this.

00:03:39.020 --> 00:03:45.100
So I opened up a script, a single R script.

00:03:45.100 --> 00:03:51.419
And I proceeded to copy the contents of the Excel model into this script.

00:03:51.419 --> 00:03:56.500
And I basically did this verbatim, because quite honestly, I didn't fully understand

00:03:56.500 --> 00:03:59.940
what was going on in the Excel model.

00:03:59.940 --> 00:04:05.580
And I'd also written on my CV that I was an advanced user of R, which wasn't quite true.

00:04:05.899 --> 00:04:09.339
But, you know, we'll live with that.

00:04:09.339 --> 00:04:10.899
And I proceeded to write the whole thing up.

00:04:10.899 --> 00:04:12.899
This was painful, but I got through it.

00:04:12.899 --> 00:04:14.940
I was really proud of myself.

00:04:14.940 --> 00:04:18.739
And I kind of thought that, like, by the end of this, like, my boss is really going to

00:04:18.739 --> 00:04:20.519
be impressed with this.

00:04:20.519 --> 00:04:23.220
It's going to really change the business.

00:04:23.220 --> 00:04:24.619
So I go away to lunch.

00:04:24.619 --> 00:04:26.380
I click run.

00:04:26.380 --> 00:04:27.779
And I'm like, great.

00:04:27.779 --> 00:04:28.779
Happy days.

00:04:28.779 --> 00:04:30.500
I'm on cloud nine.

00:04:30.500 --> 00:04:35.540
Then I come back from lunch, and there's a message in my inbox.

00:04:35.540 --> 00:04:40.420
And somebody has sent an email, and it's not addressed to me.

00:04:40.420 --> 00:04:42.220
It's addressed to the team.

00:04:42.220 --> 00:04:46.260
That's the first kind of sign that you've done something really wrong.

00:04:46.260 --> 00:04:51.339
And someone says, what's the effect of I can't log on to the server?

00:04:51.339 --> 00:04:56.380
Now I'm a junior analyst at the time, so I don't really understand the consequences that

00:04:56.380 --> 00:04:58.540
I can create for other people.

00:04:58.579 --> 00:05:02.820
So my reaction to this is, well, that's a bit of a shame for you, but I hope you solve

00:05:02.820 --> 00:05:05.739
the problem soon.

00:05:05.739 --> 00:05:09.019
And then inevitably you start getting other messages.

00:05:09.019 --> 00:05:12.059
So someone else says, yeah, I can't log on.

00:05:12.059 --> 00:05:17.299
Someone else inevitably needs this server for critical work, and you're blocking it.

00:05:17.299 --> 00:05:20.100
And then eventually someone comes to you, and they're like, do you know what's going

00:05:20.100 --> 00:05:22.940
on, Johnny?

00:05:22.940 --> 00:05:28.459
My initial reaction is no, but then it quickly dawns on me that I kind of do have some idea

00:05:28.459 --> 00:05:31.100
of what's going wrong.

00:05:31.100 --> 00:05:36.179
That very last shred of denial is quickly eroding, and I finally realize that something

00:05:36.179 --> 00:05:38.739
I've done has caused this mess.

00:05:38.739 --> 00:05:41.339
And I realize that I crashed the server.

00:05:41.339 --> 00:05:46.940
Now I put a celebratory emoji there, because I think this is a bit of a badge of honor.

00:05:46.940 --> 00:05:50.859
If you're ever involved in this, treat it as a badge of honor.

00:05:50.859 --> 00:05:53.100
Don't treat it as a total failure.

00:05:53.100 --> 00:05:56.059
You will come through better in the end.

00:05:56.059 --> 00:06:02.660
So this was ‑‑ I jest about this, and it's kind of a funny experience in hindsight,

00:06:02.660 --> 00:06:05.980
but at the time this was kind of a serious issue.

00:06:05.980 --> 00:06:11.700
So I was working in an industry that is dominated by Microsoft Excel.

00:06:11.700 --> 00:06:15.299
In fact, Excel is like a fortress.

00:06:15.299 --> 00:06:20.500
Most models are configured in Excel, and Excel is the most trustworthy piece of software

00:06:20.500 --> 00:06:25.019
for many senior executives in these scenarios.

00:06:25.019 --> 00:06:27.420
There's a quote from The Wire.

00:06:27.420 --> 00:06:29.500
I don't know if anybody has seen The Wire.

00:06:29.500 --> 00:06:35.220
The character Omar says, if you're going to come at the king, you best not miss.

00:06:35.220 --> 00:06:39.700
And I'd just come at the king, and I'd missed pretty badly.

00:06:39.700 --> 00:06:46.859
I was lucky enough to have a boss at the time who was sympathetic enough to, you know, persevere

00:06:46.859 --> 00:06:52.380
with this project beyond my drastic failure.

00:06:52.380 --> 00:06:57.899
And so what's the moral of this story?

00:06:57.899 --> 00:06:58.899
Why am I here?

00:06:58.899 --> 00:07:01.179
What kind of advice can I give you?

00:07:01.179 --> 00:07:03.220
Let's kind of analyze what went wrong here.

00:07:03.220 --> 00:07:11.100
So the first big tip I have, and it's really the biggest fundamental problem that I encountered

00:07:11.100 --> 00:07:15.540
here is, you don't really want to copy or replicate Excel.

00:07:15.540 --> 00:07:16.540
Okay?

00:07:16.540 --> 00:07:21.059
Now, like, this is an obvious point to make to people if you're a seasoned programmer,

00:07:21.059 --> 00:07:26.339
but let's take a step back and put yourselves in the shoes of somebody who hasn't really

00:07:26.339 --> 00:07:28.980
written much code in their life.

00:07:28.980 --> 00:07:34.059
So somebody who's only ever used Excel before, for somebody like that, everything looks a

00:07:34.059 --> 00:07:36.980
bit like this.

00:07:36.980 --> 00:07:39.019
And that's a spreadsheet.

00:07:39.019 --> 00:07:45.540
But if you think about it visually, it's a bit like a data frame in R. And that's not

00:07:45.540 --> 00:07:46.540
a mistake.

00:07:46.540 --> 00:07:50.420
But Excel models a lot of things using data frames.

00:07:50.420 --> 00:07:56.739
And whilst this isn't a problem in itself, you end up with a lot of Excel models which

00:07:56.739 --> 00:07:58.700
have a few questionable design choices.

00:07:58.700 --> 00:08:04.779
So the first issue you encounter typically in the wild is Excel models which start out

00:08:04.779 --> 00:08:10.700
with, you know, a few number of tabs of slowly increasing levels of information, and you

00:08:10.700 --> 00:08:15.820
think we're okay, we're stable, and then by the end of it, you've got hundreds of tabs.

00:08:16.100 --> 00:08:20.140
And if you're the creator of this model, you typically end up having a nervous sweat any

00:08:20.140 --> 00:08:22.140
time anybody else needs to use it.

00:08:22.140 --> 00:08:24.940
It's a very precarious situation to be in.

00:08:24.940 --> 00:08:30.220
And all of this comes about because the most natural data structure to use when you're

00:08:30.220 --> 00:08:34.820
using Excel is a data frame object.

00:08:34.820 --> 00:08:38.179
So this is one issue that you encounter sometimes.

00:08:38.179 --> 00:08:45.020
The second is a lot of these models, you can store data just in a spreadsheet or in a data

00:08:45.020 --> 00:08:46.020
frame.

00:08:46.020 --> 00:08:48.940
So you don't really need a database, right?

00:08:48.940 --> 00:08:50.260
Well, not quite.

00:08:50.260 --> 00:08:56.059
I mean, a lot of these models probably should be supported by a database, but they're not.

00:08:56.059 --> 00:08:57.700
And that's nobody's fault, right?

00:08:57.700 --> 00:09:02.719
Like a lot of analysts who have built these models don't necessarily have the knowledge

00:09:02.719 --> 00:09:09.539
or the skills to even think about databases, let alone implement a database.

00:09:09.539 --> 00:09:15.940
Apparently at the time when I was doing this, I wasn't aware of this as an option.

00:09:15.940 --> 00:09:17.739
Now why am I mentioning all this?

00:09:17.739 --> 00:09:19.500
These are issues with Excel models.

00:09:19.500 --> 00:09:26.419
But the point is, if you're migrating an existing model into an R environment, you definitely

00:09:26.419 --> 00:09:30.419
don't want to be copying over these design choices.

00:09:30.419 --> 00:09:37.020
If you do this, then you're only going to reintroduce the problems in a different context.

00:09:37.020 --> 00:09:40.179
So what's my next tip off the back of this?

00:09:40.179 --> 00:09:46.500
So what you want to do, instead of kind of copying what's going on in the existing platform,

00:09:46.500 --> 00:09:51.659
which is Excel in this case, you want to think about the structure of this model.

00:09:51.659 --> 00:09:57.539
So what you want to do is abstract away the implementation that you see in Excel and think

00:09:57.539 --> 00:10:00.559
about, well, what is it actually trying to do, right?

00:10:00.559 --> 00:10:02.799
What are the functional requirements?

00:10:02.799 --> 00:10:04.719
What is this model trying to achieve?

00:10:04.719 --> 00:10:10.760
And the first fundamental step of this process is where does my model begin and where does

00:10:10.760 --> 00:10:11.760
it end?

00:10:11.760 --> 00:10:15.440
And that can be pretty tricky with some of these Excel models.

00:10:15.440 --> 00:10:20.520
They are so monolithic that it's actually very hard sometimes to know where the calculations

00:10:20.520 --> 00:10:22.840
begin and where they end.

00:10:22.840 --> 00:10:26.880
But this is a process that you have to go through in order to start unpicking this object

00:10:26.880 --> 00:10:29.559
and migrating it across.

00:10:29.559 --> 00:10:31.799
So this is why I have this A to B presented here.

00:10:31.880 --> 00:10:36.400
So you want to kind of know, how do I get from point A to point B?

00:10:36.400 --> 00:10:38.280
That's the first ingredient.

00:10:38.280 --> 00:10:44.799
The second thing is, well, along that route, what are the operations that I'm applying

00:10:44.799 --> 00:10:49.479
to the data at point A to get to point B?

00:10:49.479 --> 00:10:54.260
And if you're doing a migration, especially in R or any language, really, these are really

00:10:54.260 --> 00:10:59.320
important things to identify, because you'll be able to encapsulate these into functions

00:10:59.320 --> 00:11:03.119
and objects that you can use in your programming environment.

00:11:03.119 --> 00:11:09.599
So this is a good kind of planning scheme to go through before you actually do anything.

00:11:09.599 --> 00:11:14.280
And the second thing kind of related to this is you want to think about, what are the data

00:11:14.280 --> 00:11:19.159
structures that I need to transport the data along this route?

00:11:19.159 --> 00:11:20.159
Okay.

00:11:20.159 --> 00:11:24.400
Just because the Excel model that you're looking at is doing everything in Excel and you've

00:11:24.400 --> 00:11:29.299
got multiple tabs and multiple bits of information hanging in memory, it doesn't mean that

00:11:29.299 --> 00:11:33.380
you need to do the exact same thing when you migrate this into R.

00:11:33.380 --> 00:11:39.659
In fact, you could probably save a lot of the hassle, a lot of the overuse of this memory

00:11:39.659 --> 00:11:43.979
and all the other problems that come with it by just thinking about, what do I need

00:11:43.979 --> 00:11:47.659
to retain as I go from A to B?

00:11:47.659 --> 00:11:52.299
So let me kind of put this into context with an example.

00:11:52.299 --> 00:11:57.580
So I mentioned earlier that I've been working on a simulation model at this time.

00:11:57.580 --> 00:12:02.219
Now, not to go into too much detail, but the simulation model in each outcome, it would

00:12:02.219 --> 00:12:09.460
generate one simulation which had a set of 30 numeric outputs across 30 different risk

00:12:09.460 --> 00:12:11.940
classes.

00:12:11.940 --> 00:12:19.140
And one stage of this model is involve the task of trying to aggregate these simulations

00:12:19.140 --> 00:12:20.599
together.

00:12:20.599 --> 00:12:26.299
So the author of the Excel model decided that, well, the best idea that we can use in this

00:12:26.340 --> 00:12:30.900
context is we'll take the current simulation that you can see on the screen here, and then

00:12:30.900 --> 00:12:36.260
we'll take the previous simulations, OK, the previous set of simulations, we'll add that

00:12:36.260 --> 00:12:41.020
on to the existing set, and then we'll get another set of simulations that is one row

00:12:41.020 --> 00:12:43.900
bigger than the previous.

00:12:43.900 --> 00:12:49.859
And that would go on recursively until you got to, in this case, the 15 millionth iteration.

00:12:49.859 --> 00:12:53.940
So yeah, this was something you needed to execute across multiple spreadsheets, and

00:12:53.940 --> 00:12:57.419
it was a slow process.

00:12:57.419 --> 00:12:58.580
But here's the problem, right?

00:12:58.580 --> 00:13:03.780
If you kind of replicate this approach and you just stick it in an R script, you're going

00:13:03.780 --> 00:13:07.099
to run into trouble really quickly.

00:13:07.099 --> 00:13:09.580
And it'll look something a bit like this.

00:13:09.580 --> 00:13:15.900
And this is like a classic problem that you'll encounter in the R programming world, which

00:13:15.900 --> 00:13:20.940
is copying objects in loops unnecessarily.

00:13:20.940 --> 00:13:27.140
And unfortunately, like, this is one of the key design flaws that I had first implemented

00:13:27.140 --> 00:13:33.219
in my script, which meant that this thing would just eat up your memory and it would

00:13:33.219 --> 00:13:35.359
keep on going for ages.

00:13:35.359 --> 00:13:40.059
You probably wouldn't get to the end of this on 15 million iterations, at least within

00:13:40.059 --> 00:13:41.059
a few days.

00:13:41.059 --> 00:13:46.799
So this was a really, like, key design flaw in the way I had structured this.

00:13:46.799 --> 00:13:49.299
So how did I fix this in the end?

00:13:49.299 --> 00:13:56.900
So I thought about it in a more abstract way, and I abstracted away from whatever the

00:13:56.900 --> 00:14:01.260
model was doing initially, and I thought, well, what I actually need to generate here

00:14:01.260 --> 00:14:07.739
is a list of simulation results, and that will be equal to the length of the number

00:14:07.739 --> 00:14:10.780
of simulations I want to run.

00:14:10.780 --> 00:14:16.260
And for each of these entries in this list, I just need a function that will generate

00:14:16.260 --> 00:14:23.460
my simulation results across these 30 RISC classes, and then I just need to run this

00:14:23.460 --> 00:14:28.059
again and again until I get to the very end.

00:14:28.059 --> 00:14:31.859
And then we just need to bind these together.

00:14:31.859 --> 00:14:37.020
So this looks simple and, like, it was kind of a subtly different way of designing this,

00:14:37.020 --> 00:14:43.619
but this very different way of doing this was actually, like, a massive improvement

00:14:43.979 --> 00:14:47.580
on the existing script that I had written.

00:14:47.580 --> 00:14:51.780
And it's small tweaks like that where you think about the requirements, what you're

00:14:51.780 --> 00:14:56.320
trying to do, which have quite a significant effect on the performance.

00:14:56.320 --> 00:15:03.419
So my key tip here, as I've said already, is to structure your model.

00:15:03.419 --> 00:15:06.900
And the final tip I have here is try to keep things simple.

00:15:06.900 --> 00:15:11.700
So one of the problems is, and I don't know what possessed me to do this at the time,

00:15:11.700 --> 00:15:16.539
but as a budding analyst, I thought it might be a good idea to, you know, try and do a

00:15:16.539 --> 00:15:20.020
bit of parallel processing in this script.

00:15:20.020 --> 00:15:25.580
And I think this was the straw that broke the camel's back in my case.

00:15:25.580 --> 00:15:30.940
Coupled with some of the other design flaws that I'd implemented, I was trying to do multi-threaded

00:15:30.940 --> 00:15:33.820
processing and it all went a bit wrong.

00:15:33.820 --> 00:15:36.900
I didn't really read the documentation properly.

00:15:36.900 --> 00:15:40.780
And I kind of was overcomplicating things, right?

00:15:40.900 --> 00:15:44.419
Was this really a concern that I needed to address?

00:15:44.419 --> 00:15:46.419
The answer is no.

00:15:46.419 --> 00:15:52.099
What I really needed to do with this process was start simple and start with a sample of

00:15:52.099 --> 00:15:54.580
iterations that I'm trying to run.

00:15:54.580 --> 00:16:00.059
And then I want to build this up gradually, profile what I'm doing, and work from there.

00:16:00.059 --> 00:16:05.260
So doing the basics right in these cases can be really important.

00:16:05.260 --> 00:16:13.700
So with that, I want to thank you for listening, and I want to just leave you with this quote

00:16:13.700 --> 00:16:19.219
from Bob Ross, which I really like, is that, you know, you make mistakes, and we all make

00:16:19.219 --> 00:16:23.780
mistakes in life, and it's a cliché, but I like the addition that mistakes are just

00:16:23.780 --> 00:16:25.700
happy accidents, right?

00:16:25.700 --> 00:16:30.539
Like now I can jest about this and I can be happy about my accident, because I actually

00:16:30.539 --> 00:16:33.659
learned a lot in the long run.

00:16:33.659 --> 00:16:35.659
So thank you all for listening.

00:16:35.659 --> 00:16:36.659
That's the end.

00:16:36.659 --> 00:16:37.659
Thank you.

00:16:37.659 --> 00:16:38.659
Yeah.

00:16:38.659 --> 00:16:38.659


